<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Legacy Auto Backup rules, used on API 30 (Ramblr's minSdk) through API 30. API 31+ devices use
  data_extraction_rules.xml instead (see android:dataExtractionRules in AndroidManifest.xml), but
  this file is kept as the pre-31 fallback and because some OEM backup agents still consult it.

  Everything in the plain "ramblr" SharedPreferences file is safe and desirable to restore to a
  new device: Advanced settings (auto-hide delay/toggle, peek sliver size, raw-text retry, history
  enabled), overlay appearance, personas, provider chain ordering, and per-app persona mappings all
  live there and have zero device-specific state baked in.

  The Keystore-backed EncryptedSharedPreferences files are deliberately excluded (there are three:
  ramblr_secure.xml for the legacy single OpenAI key, ramblr_provider_credentials.xml for the
  cloud provider chain's per-provider keys, and ramblr_cleanup_credentials.xml for cleanup-specific
  credentials (see ApiKeyStore/ProviderCredentialStore/CleanupCredentialStore). All three are
  encrypted with a key generated in, and never leaving, this specific device's Android Keystore
  (hardware-backed on most devices). If their ciphertext were restored to a new phone, the new
  device's Keystore has no way to produce the same key, so every read would either come back empty
  or throw: silently broken cloud credentials at best, a crash on first read at worst. Excluding
  them means the user re-enters their API key(s) once on a new device, which is the correct/safe
  behavior anyway.

  Note this file uses include-only semantics: once any <include> is present, everything NOT
  explicitly included is already omitted by default. The <exclude> lines below are kept anyway,
  as an explicit, self-documenting guard against ever regressing this by accident (e.g. a future
  wildcard include). ramblr_model_catalog_cache.xml (a plain, non-secret network cache) is
  intentionally omitted from both the include and exclude lists: there's nothing sensitive in it,
  but it's a cache and will simply refetch, so it isn't worth restoring either.
-->
<full-backup-content>
    <include domain="sharedpref" path="ramblr.xml" />

    <!-- User's chosen custom overlay icon (#43/#53): a small PNG in app-private files storage,
         not device-specific, safe and desirable to carry over to a new device. -->
    <include domain="file" path="overlay_icon.png" />

    <exclude domain="sharedpref" path="ramblr_secure.xml" />
    <exclude domain="sharedpref" path="ramblr_provider_credentials.xml" />
    <exclude domain="sharedpref" path="ramblr_cleanup_credentials.xml" />
</full-backup-content>
